    "Evaluation": {
      "text": "Clinical diagnosis in ED\nCan be aided by histopathology\nIf there is an affected joint it is important to evaluate for a\nseptic arthritis\nIf there are draining wounds consider imaging and evaluate for\nosteomyelitis",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": [
        {
          "text": "septic arthritis",
          "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/Septic_arthritis"
        },
        {
          "text": "osteomyelitis",
          "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/Osteomyelitis"
        }
      ]
    },
    "Management": {
      "text": "Long-term antibiotic therapy (2-18 weeks)\nMonotherapy with\ndoxycycline\n,\nclarithromycin\n,\nbactrim\n, or\nminocycline\n[3]\n[4]\nSecondary to drug high levels of drug resistance, may require dual drug therapy\nWarm compresses (bacterium is heat-sensitive)",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": [
        {
          "text": "doxycycline",
          "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/Doxycycline"
        },
        {
          "text": "clarithromycin",
          "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/Clarithromycin"
        },
        {
          "text": "bactrim",
          "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/Bactrim"
        },
        {
          "text": "minocycline",
          "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/Minocycline"
        }
      ]
    },
    "Disposition": {
      "text": "Unless the patient has evidence of sepsis, severe pain, or has other severe complicating medical problems, outpatient treatment is acceptable.",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": []
    },
    "Clinical_Course": {
      "text": "M marinum infection may result in non-healing ulcers or a septic arthritis.\nAggressive or long standing .  marinum infection may cause severe osteomyelitis requiring surgical debreedment",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": []
    },
